            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Kenji Miller\u2019s life story is one of synthesis, born from the blend of his Japanese father's quiet, stoic precision and his Caucasian mother's expressive, bohemian spirit. Raised in the East Bay, he was a thoughtful child, equally fascinated by the intricate emotions behind people's faces and the way charcoal could capture them on paper. This duality led him to San Francisco State University, where he cobbled together a major from Psychology and Fine Arts courses, searching for a language that could bridge the internal and external worlds.\n\nHis formal education was cut short in his junior year. His mother was diagnosed with a degenerative illness, and Kenji left school to become one of her primary caregivers. This period became his true education. He witnessed firsthand how his mother, losing her mobility, found immense solace and a voice in the small watercolor paintings she could create from her bed. It was here that Kenji\u2019s career path crystallized; the connection between art and healing was no longer an academic theory but a profound, lived reality.\n\nAfter his mother passed away, Kenji didn't return to complete his degree. Instead, he channeled his experience into vocational training, earning a certificate in Art Therapy. He began working for a non-profit that partnered with schools and community health clinics, finding his calling in helping troubled youth and isolated seniors process trauma through creative expression.\n\nNow 44, Kenji lives a life of intentional calm in the Inner Richmond. His 2.5-mile bicycle commute, often cutting through Golden Gate Park, is a meditative start and end to his day. He shares a cozy, art-filled apartment with his partner of ten years, a landscape architect named David. Their days are a quiet tapestry of meaningful work, shared meals, and walks to Ocean Beach. Kenji feels deeply woven into the fabric of San Francisco, a city that embraces those who forge their own paths. His dream is to one day open a small, sliding-scale art therapy studio in his neighborhood, ensuring that the healing power he discovered through loss is accessible to all."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was nine, sitting on the living room floor, trying to draw his father\u2019s stoic face. With a piece of charcoal, he shaded the deep lines around his father\u2019s eyes. Suddenly, the man on the paper didn't look just quiet; he looked tired and full of a gentle sadness Kenji had never noticed before. In that moment, he understood that a simple line could tell a secret story. This realization planted the seed of his life's work: to uncover the emotions hidden in plain sight.\n\n2.\nHe remembers the exact shade of blue. His mother, her hands trembling, had just finished a small watercolor of the sky outside her window. She could barely speak, but she held up the painting, her eyes filled with a pride and peace he hadn\u2019t seen in months. The painting wasn't just paper; it was her voice, her freedom. In that quiet room during his junior year of college, his academic theories shattered and reformed into a single, undeniable truth: art was a lifeline. He knew then his education would take a different path.\n\n3.\nIt was his first year as an art therapist. A silent, withdrawn teenager named Maria had refused to speak for weeks. Kenji just gave her paper and pastels. One afternoon, she filled the entire page with a chaotic, violent storm cloud. Then she finally looked at him and whispered, \u201cIt\u2019s like that inside.\u201d It was a gut punch of a moment, a profound confirmation that he had chosen the right path. He wasn't just helping people make art; he was helping them build a bridge out of their own isolation.\n\n4.\nOn their third date, about ten years ago, he took David to Ocean Beach at dusk. They walked for an hour without saying much, the fog swallowing the sound of the city behind them. As the sky turned a bruised purple, David stopped and simply pointed out the unique gradient where the wet sand met the dry. In that small, shared observation of beauty, Kenji felt a profound sense of ease. He wasn't performing or explaining himself; he was just seen. It was the quiet beginning of the home they built together.\n\n5.\nLast Tuesday, cycling home through Golden Gate Park, the evening light filtered through the eucalyptus trees, dappling the path. He felt the easy rhythm of the pedals, the cool air on his face, and was struck by a sense of potent calm. This commute wasn't just a route; it was a ritual connecting his work in the city to his life with David. He realized this feeling\u2014this grounded, purposeful peace\u2014was exactly what he wanted to offer others in his own studio. The dream felt less like an ambition and more like a promise."
